tive to pain, touch and temperature","Lower three-quarters has somatic innervation sensitive to stretch only","Lower quarter has somatic innervation sensitive to stretch only","Lower half has somatic innervation sensitive to pain, touch and temperature"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vagina has two distinct patterns of sensory innervation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elower quarter\u003C/strong\u003E receives somatic innervation via the pudendal nerve and is richly supplied with sensory nerve endings that detect pain, touch and temperature, whilst the upper three-quarters receives visceral innervation and primarily responds to stretch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elower three-quarters\u003C/strong\u003E having somatic innervation sensitive to pain, touch and temperature extends the somatic innervation too far proximally, as only the distal quarter has this type of innervation. Similarly, the \u003Cstrong\u003Elower three-quarters\u003C/strong\u003E being sensitive to stretch only mischaracterises both the extent and type of innervation in this region. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elower quarter\u003C/strong\u003E being sensitive to stretch only incorrectly describes the sensory modalities, as this region detects pain, touch and temperature rather than stretch. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elower half\u003C/strong\u003E having somatic innervation sensitive to pain, touch and temperature overestimates the extent of somatic innervation, which is limited to the lower quarter.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The lower quarter of the vagina has somatic innervation (pudendal nerve) and is sensitive to pain, touch and temperature","The upper three-quarters of the vagina has visceral innervation and is primarily sensitive to stretch"],"references":["Li T, Liao Q, Zhang H, Gao X, Li X, Zhang M. Anatomic distribution of nerves and microvascular density in the human anterior vaginal wall: prospective study. 